Part II - Interesting Interactions in the Ford GoBike Dataset¶

by Tayo Olowu¶

Summary of Key Insights¶

  • Most of the trips were fairly short in duration (about 11 minutes long), but a small proportion of trips were quite long.
  • Some factors correlated quite strongly with longer trip durations, or higher average durations. These include...
    • User age/age group
    • Time of the day during which the trip started
    • Route of trip. A route means the start station and end station pair.
    • A few other factors such as the user type (Member/Subscriber) had a slight but noticeable correlation.
  • There were two hours for each day during which the number of trips taken increased. These times were 8AM and 5PM respectively.
    • However that trend did not extend to weekends (Saturdays and Sundays).
  • Many users seemed to prefer taking trips on Tuesdays and Thursdays compared to other days.
  • There was some noticeable variation in the frequency of 'routes' taken. A 'route' means the start station and end station pair.

Investigation Overview¶

  • For this presentation, I'll focus mostly on how the trip duration (average or actual minute count) relates with some of the other variables.

    • These will include the user age, user type (Subscriber or Customer), the start time for the trip, the weekday and also 'routes' (i.e. start-station/end-station pair).

  • Next, I will count the number of trips started or ended for each hour. I'll also explain the significance of the fact that the frequency distribution of trips for start hours is nearly the same as that for the end hours.

  • The above will lead into an exploration of the distribution of trips for each weekday.

  • To close things off, I will explore the counts for the most frequented 'routes'.

Dataset Overview¶

This data set includes information about over 150,000 individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area within the month of February, 2019. It includes information about where the trip started, where it ended, and how long it lasted. It also includes basic information about the customers such as their age and gender.

# convert columns to datetime
columns = ['start_time','end_time']
for col in columns:
    df_ford[col] = pd.to_datetime(df_ford[col])

# some further wrangling
# to bin the ages into groups of ten items each.
# set right=False.
age_group_bins = [a for a in range(18, 10+df_ford['user_age'].max(), 10)]

# initialise with left endpoints, then append right endpoints
age_group_labels = [f'{a}' for a in age_group_bins[0:-1]]
b = [f'{a}' for a in age_group_bins[1:]] # selects the right endpoints
for i in range(len(age_group_labels)):
    age_group_labels[i] += f'-{int(b[i])-1}'

# creating the age-group column
df_ford['age_group'] = pd.cut(x=df_ford['user_age'], bins=age_group_bins, labels=age_group_labels,
                              right=False)

# more wrangling to make a start hour column
# for getting the hour of the time
def get_hours(column):
    return np.array(df_ford[column].dt.hour)

# we'll need this specific column later
df_ford['start_hour'] = get_hours('start_time')

# more wrangling
# creating a part of day column
# dont forget to set right=False to get [a.b) instead of (a,b]
dpart_bins = [0]+[i for i in range(6,27,3)]
#print(dpart_bins)
dpart_labels = ('Midnight-to-Dusk','Early Morning',
                'Late Morning','Early Afternoon',
                'Late Afternoon','Early Evening','Late Evening')
#print(dpart_labels)

# finally create the column 'part_of_day'
df_ford['part_of_day'] = pd.cut(df_ford['start_hour'], bins=dpart_bins,
                               labels=dpart_labels, right=False)

# make this categorical so the order is automatically respected.
weekday_order = ('Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday')
df_ford['weekday'] = pd.Categorical(df_ford['weekday'],categories=weekday_order, ordered=True)

# useful functions and constants 
# defining some useful colors
rich_orange = (0.9, 0.5, 0.1)
grayish_blue = (0.3,0.4,0.5)
grayish_gray = (0.46,0.47,0.46)

# function for quick histograms
def sketch_hist(column,stepsize,custom_x=False,color='orange',data=df_ford):
    if custom_x:
        # expects column to be a numpy array
        x = column
        lowest = np.min(column) # or amin
        largest = np.max(column)
    elif not custom_x:
        x = data[column]
        lowest = data[column].min()
        largest = data[column].max()
    bins = np.arange(lowest,largest+stepsize,stepsize)
    plt.hist(x=x, bins=bins, color=color)

# more useful functions
# for plotting the labels.
def put_labels(title, x_label, y_label):
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.ylabel(y_label)

# for conveniently placing custom tick labels
def place_ticks(least, most, step, offset=0, tick_labels=[], axis='x'):
    tick_placement = np.arange(least+offset,
                      most+step+offset,
                      step)
    tick_labels = np.array([i for i in range(least, most+step, step)]) # modfified this
    if axis=='x':
        plt.xticks(tick_placement, tick_labels)
    elif axis=='y':
        plt.yticks(tick_placement, tick_labels)

# to change the labels of the x and y axes
def label_size(n):
    axes = plt.gca()
    axes.title.set_size(n)
    axes.xaxis.label.set_size(n)
    axes.yaxis.label.set_size(n)

Part 1 - Interactions regarding trip duration¶

What factors had a noticeable correlation with trip duration?

1A - Distribution of trip durations (linear plot)¶

Trip durations in the dataset take on a large range of values, ranging from 60 seconds to nearly 23 hours. If we plot them on a linear scale, we get a very sparse visualisation because of the long tail. However, we see that the frequency peaks around 5-10 minutes if we limit our x-view.

1C - Trip duration and User Type¶

Did the Subscribers have a higher average trip duration that the Customers? Was it the opposite, or were both groups nearly balanced? As we'll see in the following box plots, the median trip duration for Subscribers is consistently less than the median for Customers. This means that a majority (50 percent) of Subscribers had shorter trip durations than a majority (50 percent) of Customers.

While it's tempting to explain this as being due to differences in pricing, the pricing plans (\$25 monthly for Subscribers, \\$3 or \$10 per trip for Customers), the pricing plans aren't that easy to compare. If a user is going to use the service only once, there's no reason for them to pay \\$25 for a month.

1D - Trip duration and Start time¶

Let's see how the start time for each trip relates to the average duration. We'll be treating start times categorically but ordinally (i.e. in an ordered fashion) as parts of the day.

Both plots tell us that the mean (average) trip duration spikes up around Midnight-to-Dusk (i.e. 12AM to before 6AM). The second one shows that trips started specifically between 3AM to 4AM have the longest average.

One possible explanation for why these nightly trips have such long average durations, is that some users started the trips and were unable to find start stations to end their trips before morning. It's also possible that they were too tired to end their trips, or that they were up all night. There isn't enough data in the dataset to make such specific conclusions, but those are interesting hypotheses.

Apart from those, notice that the Early Afternoon period (12PM to before 3PM) has right about the same average trip duration as Midnight-to-Dusk, but with more consistency (judging from the length of the error bar).

1E - Trip duration and Weekday¶

What days of the week account for the longest trip durations?

Saturdays and Sundays account for the longest average trip durations. If we put two and two together, we can conclude that, on average, the longest trips...

  • Started anywhere between Midnight and 6AM
    • Or started around Early Afternoon, which is 12PM to 3PM
  • Were taken by either the youngest or oldest users
  • Started on Saturdays or Sundays

Because those demographics aren't necesarily associated with a regular work schedule, we could hypothesize that most of the longest trips were recreational in nature.

Part 2 - Most users seemed to prefer taking trips on Tuesdays and Thursdays¶

It's something we'll observe both from the overall counts and from comparing other variables against weekday. I can't think of any good explanation for it, and there doesn't seem like there's anything in the dataset which can put this trend in a new light.

One simple explanation is that more start stations opened up on Tuesdays and Thursdays during the month the data was recorded.

2A - The total number of trips counted for each weekday shows a bimodal distribution¶

Tuesday and Thursday recorded the highest number of trips for any given day.

3C - A closer look at the relationship between Start time and End time¶

We noticed that the frequency distribution for the number of trips started looked very similar to that of the number of trips ended, and even had peaks at the same times of the day. Let's plot both of them side-by-side, noticing how their shapes and trends are similar except for small differences in height.

plt.legend() ;

One possible explanation for the similarity of shape¶

The reason for the similarity in shape is that most of the trip durations were fairly short.

It may seem obvious that the start and end hour plots should have the same shape, but that's not necessarily guaranteed. We can imagine a different Bike-sharing programme with poor logistics which somehow only has one (or a shortage of) end stations, and all those end stations open and close during a very small window for each day (say, 5PM-8PM).

All else being equal (e.g start stations being available, people starting trips as usual), the poor logistics of the end stations would force all trips to end within the same narrow window of time on any given day. In that case, the frequency distribution of the number of trips ended at a specific hour would look aggressively unimodal and peak around 5PM-8PM because no matter when the users started, they could only end their trips around that specific time of day.

However, this Bike-sharing programme doesn't seem to be like that. Most users could end their trips shortly after they started, and considering the broad geographical distribution of the Bike-sharing programme this could indicate good logistics. Still, there are small differences in height between the bars. What could explain that?

Explaining the differences in height between the bars¶

Let's make a few assumptions. First, we assume that a vast majority of the users ended their trip at most one hour after they started. This is justified from the average trip duration. What this means for the visualisation is that the height of any end-of-trip bar is overwhelmingly due to...

  • Users who started in the immediate previous start hour (e.g started by 10:00 AM and ended by 11:00 AM, or started by 10:50 AM and ended by 11:10 AM)
  • Users who started within in the same hour (e.g. started by 10:30 AM and ended by 10:40 AM)

For a given hour, there are two possible cases, keeping in mind that the average trip duration is fairly short (about 11 minutes). Let's say it's an hour at best.

  • The start bar is taller than the end bar. There are two feasible explanations for this.

    • The first explanation for this is that a number of the users started late within the current start hour and (after a short trip) ended early within the next end hour, instead of ending within same hour as the start. For example, 10:54 AM to 11:04 AM is just a ten-minute trip but it crosses an hour boundary.
    • The second is that a number of the users started early within the current hour (e.g. 10:00 AM) and after a long trip duration (say, 50 minutes) they ended within the next hour (e.g. 10:10 AM to 11:00 AM).

  • The start bar is shorter than the end bar.

    • Considering the above case, the greater height of the end bar comes from people who started in the previous hour, as well as some people who started within the same hour.

If the preceding explanations are correct, the key insight is as follows - the similarity of the distributions reinforces the fact that most of the trip durations were fairly short, and could be ended conveniently within the same hour or the next.

3D - Counts of start time for each weekday¶

We've seen what the frequency of trips taken looked like for each start time across the entire dataset. But what if we partitioned the dataset by weekday and checked the number of trips started at any given hour, for each day of the week? What will the trend reveal?

The bimodality disappears for Saturday and Sunday. In modern Industrialised societies (one of which is arguably San Francisco), Monday to Friday are work days and Saturday and Sunday are usually work-free days. The above distribution lends evidence to the hypothesis that the reason for the bimodal 'horns' is due to users rushing to and from work.

Let's also notice that on Saturdays and Sundays, the trip-taking rates spike around Early to Late Afternoon, which is 12PM to about 5PM. One explanation is that the users were taking leisurely trips around that time.

Part 4 - Popular routes¶

To close this presentation, we'll look at interactions between start stations and end stations.

A 'route' means a start-station and end-station pair. It's meant to be a very rough estimate for the actual path traced for each bike trip. We don't have nearly enough data to actually determine the actual geographical path each user took, so all we can do is estimate using routes.

The dataset contains many start and end stations - 329 of each to be exact! If we were to consider every single route, we'd be dealing with $329*329$ routes, which is quite a lot. Instead, we'll only look at the 'popular' routes, i.e. the routes consisting of the top-ten most visited start-stations, and top-ten most visited end-stations. 'Popularity' in this sense means 'frequency'.

4A - The popularity of the most frequented start and end stations¶

We'll look at a Heatmap showing the popularity of routes made up of the most frequented start and end stations. Which routes were the most used? How often were they used?

In [24]:
# Step 1 - filter the dataframe for the top five start stations and top five end stations
n = 10

topn_start = df_ford['start_station_name'].value_counts(ascending=False)[0:n]
topn_end = df_ford['end_station_name'].value_counts(ascending=False)[0:n]

# a reference to the original df, but filtered
df_topjourneys = df_ford[df_ford['start_station_name'].isin(topn_start.index)]
df_topjourneys = df_topjourneys[df_topjourneys['end_station_name'].isin(topn_end.index)]

# Step 2 - group
topj_counts = df_topjourneys.groupby(['start_station_name', 'end_station_name']).count()['duration_sec']
topj_counts = topj_counts.reset_index(name='end_station_counts')
#topj_counts

# Step 3 - pivot the table
topj_counts = topj_counts.pivot(index = 'start_station_name', columns = 'end_station_name',
                            values = 'end_station_counts') ;
#topj_counts
In [25]:
# Step 4 - make a heatmap of journey counts
plt.figure(figsize=[10,8])
ax = sb.heatmap(topj_counts, annot = True, fmt = 'd', cbar_kws = {'label' : 'trip counts'}) ;
ax.set(xlabel='end station name', ylabel='start station name',
       title='TRIP COUNTS FOR EACH ROUTE\n(route means start-station to end-station)')
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.xticks(rotation=-90) ;
label_size(12)

We can see the most popular route near the top-right. It's the brightest colour there. It started at "Berry St at 4th St" and ended at "San Francisco Ferry Building (Harry Bridges Plaza)".

327 trips may not seem like a lot given the size of the dataset, but look at the range within the same heatmap. A route like "San Francisco Caltrain Station 2 (Townsend St at 4th St)" to "San Francisco Caltrain (Townsend St at 4th St)" only had 4 trips across it.

We'd need physical geographical data to fully grasp the ramifications of this heatmap, but it's nice to know the popularity of some of the routes.

4B - Average trip duration for popular routes¶

For each of the popular routes shown previously, what's the average trip duration? Would we expect the most popular route to have the longest or the shortest trip duration?

Much credit goes to Udacity for inspiring the following code.

In [26]:
# Avg trip duration for each start and end station.
plt.figure(figsize=[10,8])

cat_means = df_topjourneys.groupby(['end_station_name', 'start_station_name']).mean()['duration_min']
cat_means = cat_means.reset_index(name = 'average_trip_duration') ;
cat_means = cat_means.pivot(index = 'start_station_name', columns = 'end_station_name',
                            values = 'average_trip_duration') ;
ax = sb.heatmap(cat_means, annot = True, fmt = '.1f', cbar_kws = {'label' : 'mean trip duration (minutes)'}) ;
ax.set(xlabel='end station name', ylabel='start station name',
       title='AVERAGE TRIP DURATIONS FOR EACH ROUTE\n(route means start-station to end-station)')

label_size(13)
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.xticks(rotation=-90) ;

The route with the longest average trip duration is the brightest colour near the top-right corner. Its name is...

  • "Berry St at 4th St" to "San Francisco Caltrain Station 2 (Townsend St at 4th St)", which had an average trip duration of 61.9 minutes (slightly over an hour long).

That route has the same start station, but it's not the same as the most frequented route, which was "Berry St at 4th St" to "San Francisco Ferry Building (Harry Bridges Plaza)". In fact, it we look at the trip counts for each route (about two previous slides) we'll see that this route with the longest average trip wasn't very popular. It hosted only 10 trips, compared to the most popular's 327 trips.

In sharp contrast, the most popular route ("Berry to Harry Bridges") had an average trip duration of 10.6 minutes, just under 11 minutes. What could this mean? That perhaps users in general prefer the shortest routes (routes which minimise time)? Perhaps. That would make sense if most of the users were trying to commute to work or leave work quickly, and it's fairly consistent if we compare the dark splotches on this heatmap (shortest average trip durations) with the bright splotches on the previous heatmap (most popular routes). The correspondence isn't perfect, but the cells almost match up.

    • README.md
    • dataset (optional)

    zip -r my_project.zip .
